{"title_page": "Adam Makos", "text_new": "{{short description|American author and historian}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Adam Makos\n| image              = Adam Makos and Dick Bonelli in talks with DPRK (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = Makos in 2013\n| birth_date         = {{birth year and age|1981}}\n| birth_place        = [[Williamsport, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| residence          = [[Denver, Colorado]]\n| nationality        = American\n| occupation         = Editor, publisher, historian, writer\n| notable_works      = ''[[Spearhead (Makos novel)|Spearhead]]''<br>''Devotion''<br>''A Higher Call''\n}}\n\n'''Adam Makos''' (born 1981) is an American writer, editor, historian and publisher.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/world-war-ii-veteran-clarence-smoyer-memories-of-a-shot-fired-spearhead/|title=A World War II veteran's memories of a shot fired|last=November 11|first=CBS News|last2=2018|website=www.cbsnews.com|language=en|access-date=2019-02-28|last3=Am|first3=9:39}}</ref> Makos specializes in war [[novels]] and [[biographies]] appearing on the [[The New York Times Best Seller list|New York Times Best Seller list]] twice for his works [[Spearhead (Makos novel)|''Spearhead'']] and ''A Higher Call''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbur.org/hereandnow/2019/02/22/wwii-veteran-sherman-tank-clarence-smoyer|title=95-Year-Old WWII Veteran Gets Surprise Visit From An 'Old Friend': A Sherman Tank|website=www.wbur.org|language=en|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref> While in [[high school]] Makos was one of the founding members of ''Valor'' a [[magazine]] depicting veterans stories ranging from [[World War I]] to [[Iraq War]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/books/2019/02/25/spearhead-wwii-book-tank-strategy-but-humanity-central-focus/2953957002/|title='Spearhead' is a WWII book on tank strategy, but humanity is central focus|website=USA TODAY|language=en|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wnep.com/2019/02/23/spearhead-book-signing-in-williamsport/|title=\u2018Spearhead\u2019 Book Signing in Williamsport|date=2019-02-23|website=WNEP.com|language=en|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mcall.com/news/local/mc-nws-allentown-wwii-sherman-tank-clarence-smoyer-20190218-story.html|title=WWII gunner 'at a loss for words' as he rides a Sherman tank in south Allentown|last=Radzievich|first=Nicole|website=themorningcall.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref>\n\nMakos has published two NY Times Best Sellers; ''Spearhead'' and ''A Higher Call'' as well as ''Voices of the Pacific'' which follows marines and seamen who served in the Pacific during [[World War II]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/book-excerpt-spearhead-the-world-war-ii-odyssey-of-an-american-tank-gunner/|title=Book excerpt: \"Spearhead: The World War II Odyssey of an American Tank Gunner\"|last=November 9|first=CBS News|last2=2018|website=www.cbsnews.com|language=en|access-date=2019-02-28|last3=Am|first3=11:54}}</ref> In 2018 it was announced Makos' third novel ''Devotion'' would be turned into a film. The release date has yet to be announced.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wwno.org/post/reading-life-chris-castellani-and-coleman-warner|title=The Reading Life with Chris Castellani and Coleman Warner|last=Larson|first=Susan|website=www.wwno.org|language=en|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fortmorgantimes.com/fort-morgan-local-news/ci_32265007/adam-makos-speaks-local-veterans-world-war-ii|title=Adam Makos speaks to local veterans on stories about World War II|website=www.fortmorgantimes.com|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/03/devotion-movie-glen-powell-adam-makos-book-korean-war-black-label-media-1202314603/|title=True Korean War Fighter Pilot Story \u2018Devotion\u2019 Set At Black Label With Glen Powell To Star|last=Hipes|first=Patrick|last2=Hipes|first2=Patrick|date=2018-03-07|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nMakos was born in [[Williamsport, Pennsylvania]] in [[Northeastern Pennsylvania]]. Makos grew up in nearby [[Montoursville, Pennsylvania|Montoursville]] and attended Lyter Elementary School and then [[Montoursville Area High School]]. Makos was a member of the school's [[French language|French club]] and was signed up for a trip to [[Paris]] until opting to go to [[Walt Disney World]] with his family. The clubs flight to Paris was [[TWA Flight 800]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2013/04/04/colorado-author-adam-makos-on-war-and-memory-and-wwii-veterans/|title=Colorado author Adam Makos on war and memory and WWII veterans|date=2013-04-04|website=The Denver Post|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lehighvalleylive.com/expo/news/g66l-2019/02/18d2e45c4c1173/a-tank-rolled-down-the-streets-of-allentown-an-homage-to-a-95yearold-world-war-ii-hero.html|title=A tank rolled down the streets of Allentown, an homage to a 95-year-old World War II hero|last=February 23|first=Steve Novak {{!}} For lehighvalleylive com {{!}} Posted|last2=February 23|first2=2019 at 11:50 AM {{!}} Updated|website=lehighvalleylive.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-28|last3=PM|first3=2019 at 02:19}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nMakos has been writing for Valor since high school but his first independent novel was in 2012 when ''A Higher Call''  was released, it detailed air battles during [[World War II]] and followed the war-time lives of six airmen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.com/search?rlz=1CAACBD_enUS806US806&q=A+Higher+Call:+An+Incredible+True+Story+of+Combat+and+Chivalry+in+the+War-Torn+Skies+of+World+War+II&stick=H4sIAAAAAAAAAD3KsQrCMBRG4UEEcRKf4MdRkDq71Sxmcmigc9pEE3qbK9e0kNfxSbWL2-HjbFb7bTVW51cvMtPh37kcd_WUA4vhK_NwT1Q-a1fjFp_BC5QluqBO0KkX72JHHkYmjyazFPADisfOZtjkoEKcLf04JuTg0Vo5GZaEZoj-vcwtC7nFofUXGd1F95MAAAA&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwibyaHrqt3gAhVjnuAKHfQbCWAQxA0wHHoECAUQBA|title=A Higher Call: An Incredible True Story of Combat and Chivalry in the War-Torn Skies of World War II - Google Search|website=www.google.com|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref>  Makos saw tremendous success his first novel was on the [[New York Time Best Seller]] list for thirteen weeks and sold over 175,000 copies and 110,000 mobile ebook and audio book downloads.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/authors/185928/adam-makos|title=Adam Makos {{!}} Penguin Random House|website=PenguinRandomhouse.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref> Makos has seen success on two more novels, ''Devotion'' and ''Voices of the Pacific.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.amazon.com/Adam-Makos/e/B00B7NOG6I%3Fref=dbs_a_mng_rwt_scns_share|title=Adam Makos|website=www.amazon.com|language=en-us|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.com/search?sa=X&rlz=1CAACBD_enUS806US806&biw=1313&bih=862&q=Devotion:+An+Epic+Story+of+Heroism,+Friendship,+and+Sacrifice&stick=H4sIAAAAAAAAAONgFuLSz9U3KEguKirLUeLVT9c3NEwyzTUpzytL0RJwLC3JyC8KyXfKz8_2z8upXMRq65Jall-SmZ9npeCYp-BakJmsEFySX1SpkJ-m4JFalJ9ZnKuj4FaUmZqXUpyRWaCjkJiXohCcmFyUmZaZnAoAE-BU2m8AAAA&ved=2ahUKEwjLp9XMrN3gAhUq3IMKHZ3qArwQxA0wHHoECAoQBg|title=Devotion: An Epic Story of Heroism, Friendship, and Sacrifice - Google Search|website=www.google.com|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.com/search?sa=X&rlz=1CAACBD_enUS806US806&biw=1313&bih=862&q=Voices+of+the+Pacific:+Untold+Stories+from+the+Marine+Heroes+of+World+War+II&stick=H4sIAAAAAAAAAONgFuLSz9U3KEguKirLUeLRT9c3zMiIz04yN07TEnAsLcnILwrJd8rPz_bPy6lcxOoTlp-ZnFqskJ-mUJKRqhCQmJyZlplspRCaV5Kfk6IQXJJflAmUTivKzwUr8E0sysxLVfBILcqH6ArPLwKqC08sUvD0BACweM4CfQAAAA&ved=2ahUKEwjLp9XMrN3gAhUq3IMKHZ3qArwQxA0wHHoECAoQCg|title=Voices of the Pacific: Untold Stories from the Marine Heroes of World War II - Google Search|website=www.google.com|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Makos published a biography titled [[Spearhead (Makos novel)|''Spearhead'']] biography about a tank gunner during the [[United States]] invasion of [[Nazi Germany]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesleader.com/news/local/733733/best-selling-author-author-with-plymouth-roots-tells-lost-wwii-story|title=Best-selling author with Plymouth roots tells lost WWII story|last=timesleader|date=2019-02-17|website=Times Leader|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref> Only one week after publication the novel made its first appearance of the [[New York Times Best Seller]] list. Going as high as number 2 on the nonfiction list.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hottytoddy.com/2019/02/26/thacker-mountain-radio-hour-plays-at-the-lyric-thursday-delta-state-on-saturday/|title=Thacker Mountain Radio Hour Plays at the Lyric Thursday, Delta State on Saturday|last=Usery|first=Anna Grace|date=2019-02-26|website=HottyToddy.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pennlive.com/entertainment/2019/02/pa-world-war-ii-veteran-to-appear-with-tank-at-harrisburg-book-signing.html|title=Pa. World War II veteran to appear, with tank, at Harrisburg book signing|website=pennlive.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.easttexasmatters.com/news/top-stories/wwii-vet-hero-of-cologne-surprised-with-ride-in-tank/1806239645|title=WWII vet, 'Hero of Cologne' surprised with ride in tank|last=Necessary|first=Sue|date=2019-02-24|website=MYEASTTEX|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Adam Makos works\n!Year\n!Novel\n!Notes\n|-\n|2012\n|''A Higher Call''\n|\n|-\n|2013\n|''Voices of the Pacific''\n|\n|-\n|2014\n|''Devotion''\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|[[Spearhead (Makos novel)|''Spearhead'']]\n|NY Times Best seller one week after\npublication.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thriftbooks.com/a/adam-makos/205354/|title=Adam Makos is a journalist, historian, and editor of the military magazine, Valor. ... He is also the coauthor of the New York Times bestseller A Higher Call.|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n\n* [https://www.adammakos.com/ Official website]\n* [https://www.amazon.com/Adam-Makos/e/B00B7NOG6I%3Fref=dbs_a_mng_rwt_scns_share Adam Makos] on [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]]\n* [https://twitter.com/AdamMakos?ref_src=twsrc%5Egoogle%7Ctwcamp%5Eserp%7Ctwgr%5Eauthor Adam Makos] on [[Twitter]]\n* [https://www.facebook.com/pages/category/Author/Adam-Makos-382380358539429/ Adam Makos on Facebook]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Makos, Adam}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:American writers]]\n[[Category:American publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:People from Williamsport, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Writers from Pennsylvania]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American author and historian}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Adam Makos\n| image              = Adam Makos and Dick Bonelli in talks with DPRK (cropped).jpg\n| caption            = Makos in 2013\n| birth_date         = {{birth year and age|1981}}\n| birth_place        = [[Williamsport, Pennsylvania]], U.S.\n| residence          = [[Denver, Colorado]]\n| nationality        = American\n| occupation         = Editor, publisher, historian, writer\n| notable_works      = ''[[Spearhead (Makos novel)|Spearhead]]''<br>''Devotion''<br>''A Higher Call''\n}}\n\n'''Adam Makos''' (born 1981) is an American writer, editor, historian and publisher.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/world-war-ii-veteran-clarence-smoyer-memories-of-a-shot-fired-spearhead/|title=A World War II veteran's memories of a shot fired|last=November 11|first=CBS News|last2=2018|website=www.cbsnews.com|language=en|access-date=2019-02-28|last3=Am|first3=9:39}}</ref> Makos specializes in war [[novels]] and [[biographies]] appearing on the [[The New York Times Best Seller list|New York Times Best Seller list]] twice for his works [[Spearhead (Makos novel)|''Spearhead'']] and ''A Higher Call''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wbur.org/hereandnow/2019/02/22/wwii-veteran-sherman-tank-clarence-smoyer|title=95-Year-Old WWII Veteran Gets Surprise Visit From An 'Old Friend': A Sherman Tank|website=www.wbur.org|language=en|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref> While in [[high school]] Makos was one of the founding members of ''Valor'' a [[magazine]] depicting veterans stories ranging from [[World War I]] to [[Iraq War]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/books/2019/02/25/spearhead-wwii-book-tank-strategy-but-humanity-central-focus/2953957002/|title='Spearhead' is a WWII book on tank strategy, but humanity is central focus|website=USA TODAY|language=en|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wnep.com/2019/02/23/spearhead-book-signing-in-williamsport/|title=\u2018Spearhead\u2019 Book Signing in Williamsport|date=2019-02-23|website=WNEP.com|language=en|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mcall.com/news/local/mc-nws-allentown-wwii-sherman-tank-clarence-smoyer-20190218-story.html|title=WWII gunner 'at a loss for words' as he rides a Sherman tank in south Allentown|last=Radzievich|first=Nicole|website=themorningcall.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref>\n\nMakos has published two NY Times Best Sellers; ''Spearhead'' and ''A Higher Call'' as well as ''Voices of the Pacific'' which follows marines and seamen who served in the Pacific during [[World War II]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/book-excerpt-spearhead-the-world-war-ii-odyssey-of-an-american-tank-gunner/|title=Book excerpt: \"Spearhead: The World War II Odyssey of an American Tank Gunner\"|last=November 9|first=CBS News|last2=2018|website=www.cbsnews.com|language=en|access-date=2019-02-28|last3=Am|first3=11:54}}</ref> In 2018 it was announced Makos' third novel ''Devotion'' would be turned into a film. The release date has yet to be announced.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wwno.org/post/reading-life-chris-castellani-and-coleman-warner|title=The Reading Life with Chris Castellani and Coleman Warner|last=Larson|first=Susan|website=www.wwno.org|language=en|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fortmorgantimes.com/fort-morgan-local-news/ci_32265007/adam-makos-speaks-local-veterans-world-war-ii|title=Adam Makos speaks to local veterans on stories about World War II|website=www.fortmorgantimes.com|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2018/03/devotion-movie-glen-powell-adam-makos-book-korean-war-black-label-media-1202314603/|title=True Korean War Fighter Pilot Story \u2018Devotion\u2019 Set At Black Label With Glen Powell To Star|last=Hipes|first=Patrick|last2=Hipes|first2=Patrick|date=2018-03-07|website=Deadline|language=en|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nMakos was born in [[Williamsport, Pennsylvania]] in [[Northeastern Pennsylvania]]. Makos grew up in nearby [[Montoursville, Pennsylvania|Montoursville]] and attended Lyter Elementary School and then [[Montoursville Area High School]]. Makos was a member of the school's [[French language|French club]] and was signed up for a trip to [[Paris]] until opting to go to [[Walt Disney World]] with his family. The clubs flight to Paris was [[TWA Flight 800]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.denverpost.com/2013/04/04/colorado-author-adam-makos-on-war-and-memory-and-wwii-veterans/|title=Colorado author Adam Makos on war and memory and WWII veterans|date=2013-04-04|website=The Denver Post|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lehighvalleylive.com/expo/news/g66l-2019/02/18d2e45c4c1173/a-tank-rolled-down-the-streets-of-allentown-an-homage-to-a-95yearold-world-war-ii-hero.html|title=A tank rolled down the streets of Allentown, an homage to a 95-year-old World War II hero|last=February 23|first=Steve Novak {{!}} For lehighvalleylive com {{!}} Posted|last2=February 23|first2=2019 at 11:50 AM {{!}} Updated|website=lehighvalleylive.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-28|last3=PM|first3=2019 at 02:19}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nMakos has been writing for Valor since high school but his first independent novel was in 2012 when ''A Higher Call''  was released, it detailed air battles during [[World War II]] and followed the war-time lives of six airmen.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.com/search?rlz=1CAACBD_enUS806US806&q=A+Higher+Call:+An+Incredible+True+Story+of+Combat+and+Chivalry+in+the+War-Torn+Skies+of+World+War+II&stick=H4sIAAAAAAAAAD3KsQrCMBRG4UEEcRKf4MdRkDq71Sxmcmigc9pEE3qbK9e0kNfxSbWL2-HjbFb7bTVW51cvMtPh37kcd_WUA4vhK_NwT1Q-a1fjFp_BC5QluqBO0KkX72JHHkYmjyazFPADisfOZtjkoEKcLf04JuTg0Vo5GZaEZoj-vcwtC7nFofUXGd1F95MAAAA&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwibyaHrqt3gAhVjnuAKHfQbCWAQxA0wHHoECAUQBA|title=A Higher Call: An Incredible True Story of Combat and Chivalry in the War-Torn Skies of World War II - Google Search|website=www.google.com|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref>  Makos saw tremendous success his first novel was on the [[New York Time Best Seller]] list for thirteen weeks and sold over 175,000 copies and 110,000 mobile ebook and audio book downloads.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.penguinrandomhouse.com/authors/185928/adam-makos|title=Adam Makos {{!}} Penguin Random House|website=PenguinRandomhouse.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref> Makos has seen success on two more novels, ''Devotion'' and ''Voices of the Pacific.''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.amazon.com/Adam-Makos/e/B00B7NOG6I%3Fref=dbs_a_mng_rwt_scns_share|title=Adam Makos|website=www.amazon.com|language=en-us|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.com/search?sa=X&rlz=1CAACBD_enUS806US806&biw=1313&bih=862&q=Devotion:+An+Epic+Story+of+Heroism,+Friendship,+and+Sacrifice&stick=H4sIAAAAAAAAAONgFuLSz9U3KEguKirLUeLVT9c3NEwyzTUpzytL0RJwLC3JyC8KyXfKz8_2z8upXMRq65Jall-SmZ9npeCYp-BakJmsEFySX1SpkJ-m4JFalJ9ZnKuj4FaUmZqXUpyRWaCjkJiXohCcmFyUmZaZnAoAE-BU2m8AAAA&ved=2ahUKEwjLp9XMrN3gAhUq3IMKHZ3qArwQxA0wHHoECAoQBg|title=Devotion: An Epic Story of Heroism, Friendship, and Sacrifice - Google Search|website=www.google.com|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.com/search?sa=X&rlz=1CAACBD_enUS806US806&biw=1313&bih=862&q=Voices+of+the+Pacific:+Untold+Stories+from+the+Marine+Heroes+of+World+War+II&stick=H4sIAAAAAAAAAONgFuLSz9U3KEguKirLUeLRT9c3zMiIz04yN07TEnAsLcnILwrJd8rPz_bPy6lcxOoTlp-ZnFqskJ-mUJKRqhCQmJyZlplspRCaV5Kfk6IQXJJflAmUTivKzwUr8E0sysxLVfBILcqH6ArPLwKqC08sUvD0BACweM4CfQAAAA&ved=2ahUKEwjLp9XMrN3gAhUq3IMKHZ3qArwQxA0wHHoECAoQCg|title=Voices of the Pacific: Untold Stories from the Marine Heroes of World War II - Google Search|website=www.google.com|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Makos published a biography titled [[Spearhead (Makos novel)|''Spearhead'']] biography about a tank gunner during the [[United States]] invasion of [[Nazi Germany]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesleader.com/news/local/733733/best-selling-author-author-with-plymouth-roots-tells-lost-wwii-story|title=Best-selling author with Plymouth roots tells lost WWII story|last=timesleader|date=2019-02-17|website=Times Leader|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref> Only one week after publication the novel made its first appearance of the [[New York Times Best Seller]] list. Going as high as number 2 on the nonfiction list.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hottytoddy.com/2019/02/26/thacker-mountain-radio-hour-plays-at-the-lyric-thursday-delta-state-on-saturday/|title=Thacker Mountain Radio Hour Plays at the Lyric Thursday, Delta State on Saturday|last=Usery|first=Anna Grace|date=2019-02-26|website=HottyToddy.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pennlive.com/entertainment/2019/02/pa-world-war-ii-veteran-to-appear-with-tank-at-harrisburg-book-signing.html|title=Pa. World War II veteran to appear, with tank, at Harrisburg book signing|website=pennlive.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.easttexasmatters.com/news/top-stories/wwii-vet-hero-of-cologne-surprised-with-ride-in-tank/1806239645|title=WWII vet, 'Hero of Cologne' surprised with ride in tank|last=Necessary|first=Sue|date=2019-02-24|website=MYEASTTEX|language=en-US|access-date=2019-02-28}}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Adam Makos works\n!Year\n!Novel\n!Notes\n|-\n|2012\n|''A Higher Call''\n|\n|-\n|2013\n|''Voices of the Pacific''\n|\n|-\n|2014\n|''Devotion''\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|[[Spearhead (Makos novel)|''Spearhead'']]\n|NY Times Best seller one week after\npublication.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thriftbooks.com/a/adam-makos/205354/|title=Adam Makos is a journalist, historian, and editor of the military magazine, Valor. ... He is also the coauthor of the New York Times bestseller A Higher Call.|last=|first=|date=|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{commons category}}\n\n* [https://www.adammakos.com/ Official website]\n* [https://www.amazon.com/Adam-Makos/e/B00B7NOG6I%3Fref=dbs_a_mng_rwt_scns_share Adam Makos] on [[Amazon (company)|Amazon]]\n* [https://twitter.com/AdamMakos?ref_src=twsrc%5Egoogle%7Ctwcamp%5Eserp%7Ctwgr%5Eauthor Adam Makos] on [[Twitter]]\n* [https://www.facebook.com/pages/category/Author/Adam-Makos-382380358539429/ Adam Makos on Facebook]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Makos, Adam}}\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:American writers]]\n[[Category:American publishers (people)]]\n[[Category:People from Williamsport, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Writers from Pennsylvania]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adam_Makos"}
{"title_page": "Paco J\u00e9mez", "text_new": "{{Spanish name|J\u00e9mez|Mart\u00edn}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Paco J\u00e9mez\n| image = Paco J\u00e9mez. Marbella Football Center.jpg\n| caption = J\u00e9mez in 2013\n| fullname = Francisco J\u00e9mez Mart\u00edn\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1970|4|18|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Las Palmas]], Spain\n| height = {{height|m=1.80}}\n| position = [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|Centre back]]\n| currentclub = [[Rayo Vallecano]]  (manager)\n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = [[C\u00f3rdoba CF|C\u00f3rdoba]]\n| years1 = 1988\u20131991 | clubs1 = [[C\u00f3rdoba CF|C\u00f3rdoba]] | caps1 = 81 | goals1 = 4\n| years2 = 1991\u20131992 | clubs2 = [[Real Murcia|Murcia]] | caps2 = 35 | goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 1992\u20131993 | clubs3 = [[Rayo Vallecano]] | caps3 = 38 | goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 1993\u20131998 | clubs4 = [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a|Deportivo La Coru\u00f1a]] | caps4 = 94 | goals4 = 1\n| years5 = 1998\u20132004 | clubs5 = [[Real Zaragoza|Zaragoza]] | caps5 = 168 | goals5 = 1\n| years6 = 2004 | clubs6 = [[Rayo Vallecano]] | caps6 = 17 | goals6 = 0\n| years7 = 2005 | clubs7 = [[CD Lugo|Lugo]] | caps7 = 0 | goals7 = 0\n| totalcaps = 433 | totalgoals = 6\n| nationalyears1 = 1998\u20132001 | nationalteam1 = [[Spain national football team|Spain]] | nationalcaps1 = 21 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n| manageryears1 = 2007 | managerclubs1 = [[RSD Alcal\u00e1|Alcal\u00e1]]\n| manageryears2 = 2007\u20132008 | managerclubs2 = [[C\u00f3rdoba CF|C\u00f3rdoba]]\n| manageryears3 = 2009 | managerclubs3 = [[FC Cartagena|Cartagena]]\n| manageryears4 = 2010\u20132011 | managerclubs4 = [[UD Las Palmas|Las Palmas]]\n| manageryears5 = 2011\u20132012 | managerclubs5 = [[C\u00f3rdoba CF|C\u00f3rdoba]]\n| manageryears6 = 2012\u20132016 | managerclubs6 = [[Rayo Vallecano]]\n| manageryears7 = 2016 | managerclubs7 = [[Granada CF|Granada]] \n| manageryears8 = 2016\u20132017 | managerclubs8 = [[Cruz Azul]]\n| manageryears9 = 2017\u20132018 | managerclubs9 = [[UD Las Palmas|Las Palmas]]\n| manageryears10 = 2019\u2013 | managerclubs10 = [[Rayo Vallecano]]\n}}\n\n'''Francisco J\u00e9mez Mart\u00edn''' (born 18 April 1970), commonly known as '''Paco''' as a player, is a Spanish retired [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|central defender]], and the current [[Manager (association football)|manager]] of [[Rayo Vallecano]].\n\nOver 11 seasons, he played 269 [[La Liga]] matches in representation of three teams, mainly [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a|Deportivo]] and [[Real Zaragoza|Zaragoza]]. He appeared for [[Spain national football team|Spain]] at [[UEFA Euro 2000|Euro 2000]].\n\nPaco started working as a manager in 2007, going on to work with several clubs.\n\n==Playing career==\n===Club===\nPaco was born in [[Las Palmas]], [[Canary Islands]]. During his career he played for [[C\u00f3rdoba CF]], [[Real Murcia]], [[Rayo Vallecano]] (first appearing in [[La Liga]] and playing all 38 matches of [[1992\u201393 La Liga|the season]]), [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a]] (only appearing in a combined ten games in his first two seasons as the club achieved two consecutive runner-up spots, being more used afterwards) and [[Real Zaragoza]], which he helped to the [[2000\u201301 Copa del Rey|2001 conquest]] of the [[Copa del Rey]].<ref name=ABC>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.abc.es/nav/Navigate.exe/hemeroteca/madrid/abc/2001/07/01/066.html|title=Zaragoza, no hay quinta Copa mala|trans-title=Zaragoza, no such thing as a bad fifth Cup|newspaper=[[ABC (newspaper)|ABC]]|first=Enrique|last=Ortego|language=es|date=1 July 2001|accessdate=7 July 2014}}</ref> From January\u2013June 2004 he returned to Rayo, now in the [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|second division]]. \n\nAfter one year out of football, Paco returned to active with [[CD Lugo]] \u2013 [[Tercera Divisi\u00f3n|fourth level]] \u2013 and retired shortly after at the age of 35.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.lavozdegalicia.es/noticia/cdlugo/2015/07/01/recurso-mediaticos-lugo/0003_201507L1P41991.htm|title=El recurso de los medi\u00e1ticos del Lugo|trans-title=The recourse of Lugo's stars|newspaper=[[La Voz de Galicia]]|first=Marta|last=De Dios|language=es|date=2 July 2015|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===International===\nDuring almost three years, Paco played 21 times for the [[Spain national football team|Spanish national team]]. His debut was on 23 September 1998 in a [[Exhibition game|friendly]] against [[Russia national football team|Russia]] in [[Granada, Spain|Granada]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1998/09/24/pagina-2/406292/pdf.html|title=Camacho debuta con \u00e9pica|trans-title=Camacho has epic debut|newspaper=[[Mundo Deportivo]]|first=Jes\u00fas|last=Galindo|language=es|date=24 September 1998|accessdate=22 December 2013}}</ref> and he was a participant at [[UEFA Euro 2000]], taking part in three matches in an eventual quarter-final exit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/euro2000/789379.stm|title=Steffen stuns Spaniards|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=13 June 2000|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/euro2000/800459.stm|title=Spain survive in seven-goal classic|publisher=BBC Sport|date=21 June 2000|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/euro2000/805574.stm|title=Raul miss sends France through|publisher=BBC Sport|date=25 June 2000|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\n===Spain===\nJ\u00e9mez took up coaching in 2007, first with lowly [[RSD Alcal\u00e1]]. He moved to the second division [[2007\u201308 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|the following campaign]], with C\u00f3rdoba, being sacked with 11 matches to go.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archivo.marca.com/edicion/marca/futbol/2a_division/cordoba/es/desarrollo/1106493.html|title=El C\u00f3rdoba destituye a Paco J\u00e9mez|trans-title=C\u00f3rdoba dismiss Paco J\u00e9mez|newspaper=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|language=es|date=31 March 2008|accessdate=27 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2009, J\u00e9mez signed with [[FC Cartagena]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.laverdad.es/murcia/20090203/deportes/futbol/cartagena-despide-fabri-contrata-200902031725.html|title=El Cartagena despide a Fabri y contrata a Paco J\u00e9mez|trans-title=Cartagena fire Fabri and hire Paco J\u00e9mez|newspaper=[[La Verdad (Murcia)|La Verdad]]|first=Francisco J.|last=Moya|language=es|date=3 February 2009|accessdate=27 February 2014}}</ref> ultimately being the coach that earned the [[Region of Murcia|Murcia]] club a first ever [[2008\u201309 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|promotion to the second tier]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2009/05/24/futbol/mas_futbol/1243197248.html|title=Cartagena vuelve a Segunda 22 a\u00f1os despu\u00e9s|trans-title=Cartagena return to ''Segunda'' 22 years later|newspaper=Marca|language=es|date=24 May 2009|accessdate=27 February 2014}}</ref> He left in July.\n\nOn 12 April 2010, following [[Sergije Kre\u0161i\u0107]]'s dismissal, J\u00e9mez was appointed coach at struggling [[UD Las Palmas]] in the second level.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2010/04/12/futbol/equipos/las_palmas/1271069770.html|title=Paco J\u00e9mez es el relevo de Kresic al frente de Las Palmas|trans-title=Paco J\u00e9mez is Kresic's replacement at the helm of Las Palmas|newspaper=Marca|first=Alexis|last=Gonz\u00e1lez|language=es|date=12 April 2010|accessdate=27 February 2014}}</ref> He eventually led his hometown side safe from the relegation zone in a [[2009\u201310 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|17th-place finish]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://futbol.as.com/futbol/2010/06/20/mas_futbol/1277015223_850215.html|title=Expediente cumplido|trans-title=Mission accomplished|newspaper=[[Diario AS]]|first=Ignacio|last=S\u00e1nchez Acedo|language=es|date=20 June 2010|accessdate=27 February 2014}}</ref> being dismissed on 27 February 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://futbol.as.com/futbol/2011/02/26/mas_futbol/1298674873_850215.html|title=Las Palmas destituye a Paco J\u00e9mez tras la goleada|trans-title=Las Palmas fire Paco J\u00e9mez after rout|newspaper=Diario AS|language=es|date=26 February 2011|accessdate=27 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 June 2012, after taking C\u00f3rdoba to [[2012 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n play-offs|the first round in the division two promotion playoffs]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lavozdegalicia.es/noticia/deportes/2012/06/10/valladolid-elimina-cordoba-jugara-duelo-decisivo-ascenso-primera/00031339360915151835946.htm|title=El Valladolid elimina al C\u00f3rdoba y jugar\u00e1 el duelo decisivo por el ascenso a Primera|trans-title=Valladolid oust C\u00f3rdoba and will play ''Primera'' promotion decider|newspaper=La Voz de Galicia|language=es|date=10 June 2012|accessdate=27 February 2014}}</ref> J\u00e9mez was appointed at former club Rayo in the top flight.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.es/deportes/futbol/abci-paco-jemez-rayo-entrenador-201206220000_noticia.html|title=Paco J\u00e9mez firma con el Rayo Vallecano|trans-title=Paco J\u00e9mez signs with Rayo Vallecano|newspaper=[[ABC (newspaper)|ABC]]|language=es|date=22 June 2012|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref> After leading the team to their best-ever ranking in the competition, [[2012\u201313 La Liga|eighth]], he renewed his contract until June 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.elmundo.es/elmundodeporte/2013/05/30/futbol/1369912431.html|title=Paco J\u00e9mez renueva con el Rayo|trans-title=Paco J\u00e9mez renews with Rayo|newspaper=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]|language=es|date=30 May 2013|accessdate=27 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 May 2016, after Rayo's [[2015\u201316 La Liga|top level relegation]], J\u00e9mez failed to agree new terms<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/futbol/rayo/2016/05/25/57461685e2704e02728b45a2.html|title=Paco J\u00e9mez rechaza la oferta de renovaci\u00f3n del Rayo|trans-title=Paco J\u00e9mez refuses Rayo's renewal offer|newspaper=Marca|first=\u00c1ngel|last=Rodr\u00edguez|language=es|date=25 May 2016|accessdate=23 June 2016}}</ref> and was appointed manager at [[Granada CF]] on 20 June.<ref name=Granada>{{cite web|url=http://www.granadacf.es/noticia/paco-jemez-nuevo-entrenador-del-granada-cf|title=Paco J\u00e9mez, nuevo entrenador del Granada CF|trans-title=Paco J\u00e9mez, new manager of Granada CF|publisher=Granada CF|language=es|date=20 June 2016|accessdate=23 June 2016}}</ref> However, on 28 September, he was sacked after only six games in charge, no wins and a club-worst start to a season in more than 70 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11827/10597122/paco-jemez-sacked-by-granada-after-worst-start-for-more-than-70-years|title=Paco Jemez sacked by Granada after worst start for more than 70 years|publisher=[[Sky Sports]]|date=28 September 2016|accessdate=1 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Mexico===\nOn 28 November 2016, J\u00e9mez was named head coach of [[Cruz Azul]] in the Mexican [[Liga MX]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.us/cruz-azul/story/3007135/spaniard-paco-jemez-named-cruz-azul-coach-in-liga-mx|title=Spaniard Paco J\u00e9mez named Cruz Azul coach in Liga MX|publisher=[[ESPN FC]]|first=Tom|last=Marshall|date=28 November 2016|accessdate=1 December 2016}}</ref> He led the team to their first playoff appearance in three years. The following 27 November, he decided not renew his contract and left.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://espndeportes.espn.com/futbol/mexico/nota/_/id/3743214/paco-jemez-deja-de-ser-tecnico-de-cruz-azul|title=Paco J\u00e9mez deja de ser t\u00e9cnico de Cruz Azul|trans-title=Paco J\u00e9mez is no longer manager of Cruz Azul|publisher=[[ESPN Deportes]]|language=es|date=27 November 2017|accessdate=27 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Back to Spain===\nOn 21 December 2017, J\u00e9mez returned to Las Palmas, becoming the third permanent manager in charge of the club during [[2017\u201318 La Liga|the campaign]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.udlaspalmas.es/noticias/noticia/paco-jemez-nuevo-entrenador-de-la-ud-las-palmas|title=Paco J\u00e9mez, nuevo entrenador de la UD Las Palmas|trans-title=Paco J\u00e9mez, new manager of UD Las Palmas|publisher=UD Las Palmas|language=es|date=21 December 2017|access-date=21 December 2017}}</ref> He rejoined Rayo Vallecano in late March 2019, replacing [[M\u00edchel (footballer, born 1975)|M\u00edchel]] who had been dismissed two days earlier after losing seven league games in a row, which left the team at risk of top flight relegation, and agreeing to a deal until June 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rayovallecano.es/noticia/paco-jemez-nuevo-entrenador-del-rayo-vallecano|title=Paco J\u00e9mez nuevo entrenador del Rayo Vallecano|trans-title=Paco J\u00e9mez new coach of Rayo Vallecano|publisher=Rayo Vallecano|language=es|date=20 March 2019|accessdate=20 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Managerial statistics==\n{{updated|match played 8 March 2020}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\t\t\n |+ Managerial record by team and tenure\t\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Team\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Nat\n! rowspan=\"2\" |From\n! rowspan=\"2\"|To\n! colspan=\"8\" |Record\t\n!rowspan=2|{{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\t\t\t\n|-\n!{{Tooltip|G|Games managed}}\n!{{Tooltip|W|Games won}}\n!{{Tooltip|D|Games drawn}}\n!{{Tooltip|L|Games lost}}\n!{{Tooltip|GF|Goals for}}\n!{{Tooltip|GA|Goals against}}\n!{{Tooltip|GD|Goal difference}}\n!{{Tooltip|Win %|Winning percentage}}\t\t\t\t\t\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|[[RSD Alcal\u00e1|Alcal\u00e1]]\n|{{flagicon|Spain}}\t\n| 25 March 2007\n| 28 June 2007\n{{WDL|12|5|4|3|for=21|against=11|diff=yes}}\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=http://arquero-arba.futbolme.net/Nacionales/2006-07/0607-3-7.htm|title=Tercera Divisi\u00f3n (Grupo 7) 2006\u201307|trans-title=Tercera Divisi\u00f3n (Group 7) 2006\u201307|publisher=Futbolme|language=Spanish|accessdate=9 July 2016}}<br>{{cite web|url=http://arquero-arba.futbolme.net/Nacionales/2006-07/0607-3-asc.htm|title=Fase de ascenso a Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B  2006\u201307 |trans-title=Promotion phase to Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B 2006\u201307|publisher=Futbolme|language=Spanish|accessdate=9 July 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[C\u00f3rdoba CF|C\u00f3rdoba]]\n|{{flagicon|Spain}}\n| 28 June 2007\n| 31 March 2008\n{{WDL|32|7|15|10|for=40|against=46|diff=yes}}\t\t\t\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bdfutbol.com/en/p/l816.html?temp=2007-08|title=Paco J\u00e9mez: Francisco J\u00e9mez Mart\u00edn: Matches 2007\u201308|publisher=BDFutbol|accessdate=17 February 2016}}</ref>\t\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[FC Cartagena|Cartagena]]\n|{{flagicon|Spain}}\t\n| 3 February 2009\n| 1 July 2009\n{{WDL|19|9|7|3|for=33|against=16|diff=yes}}\t\t\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bdfutbol.com/en/p/l816.html?temp=2008-09|title=Paco J\u00e9mez: Francisco J\u00e9mez Mart\u00edn: Matches 2008\u201309|publisher=BDFutbol|accessdate=17 February 2016}}</ref>\t\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[UD Las Palmas|Las Palmas]]\n|{{flagicon|Spain}}\n| 12 April 2010\n| 27 February 2011\n{{WDL|37|9|13|15|for=52|against=69|diff=yes}}\t\t\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bdfutbol.com/en/p/l816.html?temp=2009-10|title=Paco J\u00e9mez: Francisco J\u00e9mez Mart\u00edn: Matches 2009\u201310|publisher=BDFutbol|accessdate=17 February 2016}}<br>{{cite web|url=https://www.bdfutbol.com/en/p/l816.html?temp=2010-11|title=Paco J\u00e9mez: Francisco J\u00e9mez Mart\u00edn: Matches 2010\u201311|publisher=BDFutbol|accessdate=17 February 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[C\u00f3rdoba CF|C\u00f3rdoba]]\n|{{flagicon|Spain}}\n| 8 June 2011\n| 13 June 2012\n{{WDL|50|23|13|14|for=60|against=54|diff=yes}}\t\t\t\t\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bdfutbol.com/en/p/l816.html?temp=2011-12|title=Paco J\u00e9mez: Francisco J\u00e9mez Mart\u00edn: Matches 2011\u201312|publisher=BDFutbol|accessdate=17 February 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[Rayo Vallecano]]\n|{{flagicon|Spain}}\n| 22 June 2012\n| 26 May 2016\n{{WDL|164|55|29|