0edn: Matches 2017\u201318|publisher=BDFutbol|accessdate=23 December 2017}}</ref>\n|-\n| align=\"left\" |[[Rayo Vallecano]]\n|{{flagicon|Spain}}\n| 20 March 2019\n| ''Present''\n{{WDL|44|12|20|12|for=54|against=55|diff=yes}}\t\n|<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bdfutbol.com/en/p/l816.html?temp=2018-19|title=Paco J\u00e9mez: Francisco J\u00e9mez Mart\u00edn: Matches 2018\u201319|publisher=BDFutbol|accessdate=20 March 2019}}<br>{{cite web|url=https://www.bdfutbol.com/en/p/l816.html?temp=2019-20|title=Paco J\u00e9mez: Francisco J\u00e9mez Mart\u00edn: Matches 2019\u201320|publisher=BDFutbol|accessdate=21 August 2019}}</ref>\t\n|-\n!colspan=\"4\"|Total\n{{WDLtot|435|139|127|169|for=541|against=662|diff=yes}}\t\n!\u2014\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n===Player===\n'''Deportivo'''\n*[[Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a]]: [[1995 Supercopa de Espa\u00f1a|1995]]\n\n'''Zaragoza'''\n*[[Copa del Rey]]: [[2000\u201301 Copa del Rey|2000\u201301]]<ref name=ABC/>\n\n===Manager===\n'''Cartagena'''\n*[[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]]: [[2008\u201309 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|2008\u201309]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{BDFutbol|816}}\n* {{BDFutbol manager|816}}\n* {{NFT player|id=14115}}\n* {{FIFA player|179073}}\n* [https://eu-football.info/_player.php?id=15843 Spain stats at Eu-Football]\n\n{{Spain squad UEFA Euro 2000}}\n{{Rayo Vallecano squad}}\n{{Segunda Divisi\u00f3n managers}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title= Paco J\u00e9mez \u2013 Managerial positions\n|list1=\n{{C\u00f3rdoba CF managers}}\n{{FC Cartagena managers}}\n{{UD Las Palmas managers}}\n{{Rayo Vallecano managers}}\n{{Granada CF managers}}\n{{Cruz Azul managers}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jemez, Paco}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Footballers from Las Palmas de Gran Canaria]]\n[[Category:Spanish footballers]]\n[[Category:Canarian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football defenders]]\n[[Category:La Liga players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n players]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B players]]\n[[Category:C\u00f3rdoba CF players]]\n[[Category:Real Murcia players]]\n[[Category:Rayo Vallecano players]]\n[[Category:Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a players]]\n[[Category:Real Zaragoza players]]\n[[Category:CD Lugo players]]\n[[Category:Spain international footballers]]\n[[Category:UEFA Euro 2000 players]]\n[[Category:Spanish football managers]]\n[[Category:La Liga managers]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n managers]]\n[[Category:Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B managers]]\n[[Category:RSD Alcal\u00e1 managers]]\n[[Category:C\u00f3rdoba CF managers]]\n[[Category:FC Cartagena managers]]\n[[Category:UD Las Palmas managers]]\n[[Category:Rayo Vallecano managers]]\n[[Category:Granada CF managers]]\n[[Category:Liga MX managers]]\n[[Category:Cruz Azul managers]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate football managers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate football managers in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Spanish expatriate sportspeople in Mexico]]\n", "text_old": "{{Spanish name|J\u00e9mez|Mart\u00edn}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Paco J\u00e9mez\n| image = Paco J\u00e9mez. Marbella Football Center.jpg\n| caption = J\u00e9mez in 2013\n| fullname = Francisco J\u00e9mez Mart\u00edn\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1970|4|18|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Las Palmas]], Spain\n| height = {{height|m=1.80}}\n| position = [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|Centre back]]\n| currentclub = [[Rayo Vallecano]]  (manager)\n| youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = [[C\u00f3rdoba CF|C\u00f3rdoba]]\n| years1 = 1988\u20131991 | clubs1 = [[C\u00f3rdoba CF|C\u00f3rdoba]] | caps1 = 81 | goals1 = 4\n| years2 = 1991\u20131992 | clubs2 = [[Real Murcia|Murcia]] | caps2 = 35 | goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 1992\u20131993 | clubs3 = [[Rayo Vallecano]] | caps3 = 38 | goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 1993\u20131998 | clubs4 = [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a|Deportivo La Coru\u00f1a]] | caps4 = 94 | goals4 = 1\n| years5 = 1998\u20132004 | clubs5 = [[Real Zaragoza|Zaragoza]] | caps5 = 168 | goals5 = 1\n| years6 = 2004 | clubs6 = [[Rayo Vallecano]] | caps6 = 17 | goals6 = 0\n| years7 = 2005 | clubs7 = [[CD Lugo|Lugo]] | caps7 = 0 | goals7 = 0\n| totalcaps = 433 | totalgoals = 6\n| nationalyears1 = 1998\u20132001 | nationalteam1 = [[Spain national football team|Spain]] | nationalcaps1 = 21 | nationalgoals1 = 0\n| manageryears1 = 2007 | managerclubs1 = [[RSD Alcal\u00e1|Alcal\u00e1]]\n| manageryears2 = 2007\u20132008 | managerclubs2 = [[C\u00f3rdoba CF|C\u00f3rdoba]]\n| manageryears3 = 2009 | managerclubs3 = [[FC Cartagena|Cartagena]]\n| manageryears4 = 2010\u20132011 | managerclubs4 = [[UD Las Palmas|Las Palmas]]\n| manageryears5 = 2011\u20132012 | managerclubs5 = [[C\u00f3rdoba CF|C\u00f3rdoba]]\n| manageryears6 = 2012\u20132016 | managerclubs6 = [[Rayo Vallecano]]\n| manageryears7 = 2016 | managerclubs7 = [[Granada CF|Granada]] \n| manageryears8 = 2016\u20132017 | managerclubs8 = [[Cruz Azul]]\n| manageryears9 = 2017\u20132018 | managerclubs9 = [[UD Las Palmas|Las Palmas]]\n| manageryears10 = 2019\u2013 | managerclubs10 = [[Rayo Vallecano]]\n}}\n\n'''Francisco J\u00e9mez Mart\u00edn''' (born 18 April 1970), commonly known as '''Paco''' as a player, is a Spanish retired [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|central defender]], and the current [[Manager (association football)|manager]] of [[Rayo Vallecano]].\n\nOver 11 seasons, he played 269 [[La Liga]] matches in representation of three teams, mainly [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a|Deportivo]] and [[Real Zaragoza|Zaragoza]]. He appeared for [[Spain national football team|Spain]] at [[UEFA Euro 2000|Euro 2000]].\n\nPaco started working as a manager in 2007, going on to work with several clubs.\n\n==Playing career==\nPaco was born in [[Las Palmas]], [[Canary Islands]]. During his career he played for [[C\u00f3rdoba CF]], [[Real Murcia]], [[Rayo Vallecano]] (first appearing in [[La Liga]] and playing all 38 matches of [[1992\u201393 La Liga|the season]]), [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a]] (only appearing in a combined ten games in his first two seasons as the club achieved two consecutive runner-up spots, being more used afterwards) and [[Real Zaragoza]], which he helped to the [[2000\u201301 Copa del Rey|2001 conquest]] of the [[Copa del Rey]].<ref name=ABC>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.abc.es/nav/Navigate.exe/hemeroteca/madrid/abc/2001/07/01/066.html|title=Zaragoza, no hay quinta Copa mala|trans-title=Zaragoza, no such thing as a bad fifth Cup|newspaper=[[ABC (newspaper)|ABC]]|first=Enrique|last=Ortego|language=es|date=1 July 2001|accessdate=7 July 2014}}</ref> From January\u2013June 2004 he returned to Rayo, now in the [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|second division]]; after one year out of football, he returned to active with [[CD Lugo]] \u2013 [[Tercera Divisi\u00f3n|fourth level]] \u2013 and retired at the age of 36.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.lavozdegalicia.es/noticia/cdlugo/2015/07/01/recurso-mediaticos-lugo/0003_201507L1P41991.htm|title=El recurso de los medi\u00e1ticos del Lugo|trans-title=The recourse of Lugo's stars|newspaper=[[La Voz de Galicia]]|first=Marta|last=De Dios|language=es|date=2 July 2015|accessdate=9 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nDuring almost three years, Paco played 21 times for the [[Spain national football team|Spanish national team]]. His debut was on 23 September 1998 in a [[Exhibition game|friendly]] against [[Russia national football team|Russia]] in [[Granada, Spain|Granada]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://hemeroteca.mundodeportivo.com/preview/1998/09/24/pagina-2/406292/pdf.html|title=Camacho debuta con \u00e9pica|trans-title=Camacho has epic debut|newspaper=[[Mundo Deportivo]]|first=Jes\u00fas|last=Galindo|language=es|date=24 September 1998|accessdate=22 December 2013}}</ref> and he was a participant at [[UEFA Euro 2000]], taking part in three matches in an eventual quarter-final exit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/euro2000/789379.stm|title=Steffen stuns Spaniards|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=13 June 2000|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/euro2000/800459.stm|title=Spain survive in seven-goal classic|publisher=BBC Sport|date=21 June 2000|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/euro2000/805574.stm|title=Raul miss sends France through|publisher=BBC Sport|date=25 June 2000|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\n===Spain===\nJ\u00e9mez took up coaching in 2007, first with lowly [[RSD Alcal\u00e1]]. He moved to the second division [[2007\u201308 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|the following campaign]], with C\u00f3rdoba, being sacked with 11 matches to go.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archivo.marca.com/edicion/marca/futbol/2a_division/cordoba/es/desarrollo/1106493.html|title=El C\u00f3rdoba destituye a Paco J\u00e9mez|trans-title=C\u00f3rdoba dismiss Paco J\u00e9mez|newspaper=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|language=es|date=31 March 2008|accessdate=27 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2009, J\u00e9mez signed with [[FC Cartagena]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.laverdad.es/murcia/20090203/deportes/futbol/cartagena-despide-fabri-contrata-200902031725.html|title=El Cartagena despide a Fabri y contrata a Paco J\u00e9mez|trans-title=Cartagena fire Fabri and hire Paco J\u00e9mez|newspaper=[[La Verdad (Murcia)|La Verdad]]|first=Francisco J.|last=Moya|language=es|date=3 February 2009|accessdate=27 February 2014}}</ref> ultimately being the coach that earned the [[Region of Murcia|Murcia]] club a first ever [[2008\u201309 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B|promotion to the second tier]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2009/05/24/futbol/mas_futbol/1243197248.html|title=Cartagena vuelve a Segunda 22 a\u00f1os despu\u00e9s|trans-title=Cartagena return to ''Segunda'' 22 years later|newspaper=Marca|language=es|date=24 May 2009|accessdate=27 February 2014}}</ref> He left in July.\n\nOn 12 April 2010, following [[Sergije Kre\u0161i\u0107]]'s dismissal, J\u00e9mez was appointed coach at struggling [[UD Las Palmas]] in the second level.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/2010/04/12/futbol/equipos/las_palmas/1271069770.html|title=Paco J\u00e9mez es el relevo de Kresic al frente de Las Palmas|trans-title=Paco J\u00e9mez is Kresic's replacement at the helm of Las Palmas|newspaper=Marca|first=Alexis|last=Gonz\u00e1lez|language=es|date=12 April 2010|accessdate=27 February 2014}}</ref> He eventually led his hometown side safe from the relegation zone in a [[2009\u201310 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n|17th-place finish]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://futbol.as.com/futbol/2010/06/20/mas_futbol/1277015223_850215.html|title=Expediente cumplido|trans-title=Mission accomplished|newspaper=[[Diario AS]]|first=Ignacio|last=S\u00e1nchez Acedo|language=es|date=20 June 2010|accessdate=27 February 2014}}</ref> being dismissed on 27 February 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://futbol.as.com/futbol/2011/02/26/mas_futbol/1298674873_850215.html|title=Las Palmas destituye a Paco J\u00e9mez tras la goleada|trans-title=Las Palmas fire Paco J\u00e9mez after rout|newspaper=Diario AS|language=es|date=26 February 2011|accessdate=27 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 June 2012, after taking C\u00f3rdoba to [[2012 Segunda Divisi\u00f3n play-offs|the first round in the division two promotion playoffs]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lavozdegalicia.es/noticia/deportes/2012/06/10/valladolid-elimina-cordoba-jugara-duelo-decisivo-ascenso-primera/00031339360915151835946.htm|title=El Valladolid elimina al C\u00f3rdoba y jugar\u00e1 el duelo decisivo por el ascenso a Primera|trans-title=Valladolid oust C\u00f3rdoba and will play ''Primera'' promotion decider|newspaper=La Voz de Galicia|language=es|date=10 June 2012|accessdate=27 February 2014}}</ref> J\u00e9mez was appointed at former club Rayo in the top flight.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.abc.es/deportes/futbol/abci-paco-jemez-rayo-entrenador-201206220000_noticia.html|title=Paco J\u00e9mez firma con el Rayo Vallecano|trans-title=Paco J\u00e9mez signs with Rayo Vallecano|newspaper=[[ABC (newspaper)|ABC]]|language=es|date=22 June 2012|accessdate=3 April 2020}}</ref> After leading the team to their best-ever ranking in the competition, [[2012\u201313 La Liga|eighth]], he renewed his contract until June 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.elmundo.es/elmundodeporte/2013/05/30/futbol/1369912431.html|title=Paco J\u00e9mez renueva con el Rayo|trans-title=Paco J\u00e9mez renews with Rayo|newspaper=[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]|language=es|date=30 May 2013|accessdate=27 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 May 2016, after Rayo's [[2015\u201316 La Liga|top level relegation]], J\u00e9mez failed to agree new terms<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/futbol/rayo/2016/05/25/57461685e2704e02728b45a2.html|title=Paco J\u00e9mez rechaza la oferta de renovaci\u00f3n del Rayo|trans-title=Paco J\u00e9mez refuses Rayo's renewal offer|newspaper=Marca|first=\u00c1ngel|last=Rodr\u00edguez|language=es|date=25 May 2016|accessdate=23 June 2016}}</ref> and was appointed manager at [[Granada CF]] on 20 June.<ref name=Granada>{{cite web|url=http://www.granadacf.es/noticia/paco-jemez-nuevo-entrenador-del-granada-cf|title=Paco J\u00e9mez, nuevo entrenador del Granada CF|trans-title=Paco J\u00e9mez, new manager of Granada CF|publisher=Granada CF|language=es|date=20 June 2016|accessdate=23 June 2016}}</ref> However, on 28 September, he was sacked after only six games in charge, no wins and a club-worst start to a season in more than 70 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11827/10597122/paco-jemez-sacked-by-granada-after-worst-start-for-more-than-70-years|title=Paco Jemez sacked by Granada after worst start for more than 70 years|publisher=[[Sky Sports]]|date=28 September 2016|accessdate=1 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Mexico===\nOn 28 November 2016, J\u00e9mez was named head coach of [[Cruz Azul]] in the Mexican [[Liga MX]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.us/cruz-azul/story/3007135/spaniard-paco-jemez-named-cruz-azul-coach-in-liga-mx|title=Spaniard Paco J\u00e9mez named Cruz Azul coach in Liga MX|publisher=[[ESPN FC]]|first=Tom|last=Marshall|date=28 November 2016|accessdate=1 December 2016}}</ref> He led the team to their first playoff appearance in three years. The following 27 November, he decided not renew his contract and left.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://espndeportes.espn.com/futbol/mexico/nota/_/id/3743214/paco-jemez-deja-de-ser-tecnico-de-cruz-azul|title=Paco J\u00e9mez deja de ser t\u00e9cnico de Cruz Azul|trans-title=Paco J\u00e9mez is no longer manager of Cruz Azul|publisher=[[ESPN Deportes]]|language=es|date=27 November 2017|accessdate=27 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Back to Spain===\nOn 21 December 2017, J\u00e9mez returned to Las Palmas, becoming the third permanent manager in charge of the club during [[2017\u201318 La Liga|the campaign]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.udlaspalmas.es/noticias/noticia/paco-jemez-nuevo-entrenador-de-la-ud-las-palmas|title=Paco J\u00e9mez, nuevo entrenador de la UD Las Palmas|trans-title=Paco J\u00e9mez, new manager of UD Las Palmas|publisher=UD Las Palmas|language=es|date=21 December 2017|access-date=21 December 2017}}</ref> He rejoined Rayo Vallecano in late March 2019, replacing [[M\u00edchel (footballer, born 1975)|M\u00edchel]] who had been dismissed two days earlier after losing seven league games in a row, which left the team at risk of top flight relegation, and agreeing to a deal until June 2020.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rayovallecano.es/noticia/paco-jemez-nuevo-entrenador-del-rayo-vallecano|title=Paco J\u00e9mez nuevo entrenador del Rayo Vallecano|trans-title=Paco J\u00e9mez new coach of Rayo Vallecano|publisher=Rayo Vallecano|language=es|date=20 March 2019|accessdate=20 March 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Managerial statistics==\n{{updated|match played 8 March 2020}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\t\t\n |+ Managerial record by team and tenure\t\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Team\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Nat\n! 